04463nam a22007335i 9780231513029DE-B159720220329044247.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220329t20032003nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979969455  a97802315130297 a10.7312/fran116182doi  a(DE-B1597)458863  a(OCoLC)213305346  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aJK1991 .F55 7aPOL0300002bisacsh04a324.7/8/0973a324.7809731 aFrancia, Peter, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Financiers of Congressional Elections :bInvestors, Ideologues, and Intimates /cPeter Francia, John Green, Paul Herrnson, Lynda Powell, Clyde Wilcox. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2003] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (216 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPower, Conflict, and Democracy: American Politics Into the 21st Century00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. Introduction -- t2. Who Are the Financiers of Congressional Elections? -- t3. What Motivates Donors? -- t4. Candidates, Donors, and Fundraising Techniques -- t5. The Contribution -- t6. The Donors Contact Congress -- t7. Congressional Donors and Campaign Reform -- t8. Conclusion -- tAppendix: Methodology -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex -- tBackmatter0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIndividual donors play a critical role in financing congressional elections, accounting for more than half of all money raised in House campaigns. But significant donors (defined here as those contributing more than $200) are the least understood participants in the system. Defenders assert that contributing money to campaigns is part of a broader pattern of civic involvement and is free speech that gives a voice to various interests. Detractors argue that these contributions are undemocratic, enabling wealthy citizens to overwhelm the voices of the many and to promote narrow business and policy interests. These divergent assessments were raised in connection with the Bipartisan Campaign Finance Reform Act of 2002 and continue to characterize the debate over campaign finance reform.So who really contributes and why? How much and to how many candidates? What are the strategies used by political campaigns to elicit contributions and how do the views of significant donors impact the campaign-finance system? What do donors think about campaign-finance reform? This book investigates these vital questions, describing the influence of congressional financiers in American politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aCampaign fundszUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / American Government / National.2bisacsh1 aGreen, John, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aHerrnson, Paul, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aWilcox, Clyde, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247240uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/fran1161840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231513029423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231513029/original  a978-3-11-044247-2  Columbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK